ttempted to produce a volume that incorporates most important aspects of uranium in natural systems, while providing some insight into important applications of uranium mineralogy and geochemistry to environmental problems. The result is a blend of perspectives and themes: historical (Chapter 1), crystal structures (Chapter 2), systematic mineralogy and paragenesis (Chapters 3 and 7), the genesis of uranium ore deposits (Chapters 4 and 6), the geochemical behavior of uranium and other actinides in natural fluids (Chapter 5), environmental aspects of uranium such as microbial effects, groundwater contamination and disposal of nuclear waste (Chapters 8, 9 and 10), and various analytical techniques applied to uranium-bearing phases (Chapters 11-14).This volume was written in preparation for a short course by the same title, sponsored by the Mineralogical Society of America, October 22 and 23, 1999 in Golden, Colorado, prior to MSA's joint annual meeting with the Geological Society of America.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEnvironmental geochemistry. 0aMineralogy. 0aUranium ores. 0aUraniumxEnvironmental aspects. 4aMineralogie. 4aUran. 4aUranmineralien. 4aUranverbindungen. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Mineralogy.2bisacsh1 aAbdelouas, Abdesselam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanfield, Jillian F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuck, Edgar C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, Peter C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, Peter C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEwing, Rodney C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFayek, Mostafa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo